description: First released in November 1980, Savage Action reprinted stories from Marvel US's magazines, slightly more adult fare than appeared in the US comics or UK weeklies. The only non-reprint story was Night Raven, last seen in July 1979's Hulk Comic #20, who now returned in illustrated text strips, appearing in many, but not all, issues. Since the US magazines rarely featured ongoing strips, Savage Action's strips similarly changed from issue to issue, but finally they began to stablise with the comic, not magazine, adventures of Moon Knight began Savage Action #8, soon joined by Ka-Zar's adventures from Ka-Zar the Savage. Savage Action was cancelled with #15 in January 1982; a month later it merged into Marvel Superheroes #382, which added an "incorporating Savage Action" subtitle for a single issue. The only Savage Action story to make the transition to the new title was Night Raven.
name: Savage Action

Reprinting Vampirella stories from some of the industry greats. Note that the volumes were not released in chronological order and, in some cases,the stories in the individual volumes are out of chronological order as well.

  • Vol. 2: Vampirella Lives #1-3, the story "Necromance" from Vampirella / Dracula: The Centennial, and the story "The Movement Of Blood" from Vampirella: 25th Anniversary Special
  • Vol. 3: Vampirella (2001 series) #1-6
  • Vol. 4: Vampirella (1969 series) #1, Vampirella (1997 series) #18-20, elements from Vampirella Comics Magazine #1("The Killing Floor") &10 ("Winter Rose"), the story "Matinee" from Vampirella Summer Special, the story "The New European" from Vampirella / Dracula: The Centennial, the story "Fantasy Feast" from Vampirella: Halloween Trick and Treat, Vampirella 2006 Halloween Special, and the story "Bugs" from Creepy 1993 Fearbook
  • Vol. 5: Vampirella: Morning In America #1-4, Vampirella: Summer Nights, and Vampirella (1992 series) #1-4
  • Vol. 6: Vampirella: Blood Lust #1-2, the story "Vampirella vs Dracula" from Vampirella / Dracula: The Centennial, and the story "Two So Different" from Vampirella: 25th Anniversary Special
  • Vol. 7: Elements of Vampirella (1997 series) #13-17, elements of Vampirella (2001 series) #7-10, Vampirella vs Pantha, and the story "Bound" from Vampirella Comics Magazine #5
  • Vol. 8: Vampirella Revelations #0-3, and the story "Vengeance of Vampirella" which was published across the Spring 2007, Summer 2007, and Fall 2007 editions of Vampirella Quarterly

description:
British anthology comic. Toxic! was formed by 2000AD veterans Pat Mills, Kevin O'Neill, Mike McMahon, John Wagner and Alan Grant. Unlike 2000AD (which Pat Mills launched back in 1977)Toxic! would allow creators work to be published while still retaining the rights and control over their work. Toxic! was intended to rival 2000AD by being more violent, brash and controversial, also by using full colour, unlike 2000AD which was still mainly published in black and white at the time.

Toxic! featured early work for some later well known creators such as Mike Carey, Gary Frank and characters such as Marshal Law (who had appeared earlier in Marvel's Epic line), Accident Man and Bogie Man (also appearing earlier at publisher Fat Man Press).

Despite initial strong sales, the comic failed to run strips consistently and creators were not paid on time leading to its cancellation and publisher Apocalypse being declared Bankrupt. Some of the characters found life at new publishers, such as Dark Horse and Atomeka and some even in 2000AD itself. Apocalypse did reprint most stories in the Apocalypse (1991) series.

Collected Editions

  • The Complete Accident Man (Titan Books, 2014)
  • Marshal Law: The Deluxe Edition (DC Comics, 2013)
  • Marshal Law: Fear and Loathing (Titan Books, 2002)
  • Marshal Law: Blood, Sweat and Fears (Titan Books, 2003)
  • The Bogie Man: The Manhattan Project (Tundra, 1992)
name: Toxic!
